message:
Excuse me,  
//I've read your post but I got a question can you provide me a sample where I call different consumer in parallel?  

I've seen this  

 var consumer1 = new ActionBlock(x => results1.Add(x), consumerOptions);  
 var consumer2 = new ActionBlock(x => results2.Add(x), consumerOptions);  
 var consumer3 = new ActionBlock(x => results3.Add(x), consumerOptions);  
 var linkOptions = new DataflowLinkOptions { PropagateCompletion = true, };  
 queue.LinkTo(consumer1, linkOptions);  
 queue.LinkTo(consumer2, linkOptions);  
 queue.LinkTo(consumer3, linkOptions);  

but I prefer to call them with Task.Parallel so I can parametrize how many consumer to create...thanks

Hi Stephen, thanks for taking the time to explain TPL, I think it will be suitable for creating a pipeline for processing throttled tasks, e.g. only consume xx per duration. I guess either in a specialised producer or a DataTranslation block to release tasks as soon as the duration has elapsed. Putting it in a consumer action block would loose the parallel execution. Do you have any suggestions?

Oh, the last example is more helpful if you used the following consumer definitions

 var consumer1 = new ActionBlock<int>(val => {  
 results1.Add(val);  
 Console.WriteLine($"1 consumed: {val}");  
 }, consumerOptions);  
 var consumer2 = new ActionBlock<int>(val => {  
 results2.Add(val);  
 Console.WriteLine($"2 consumed: {val}");  
 }, consumerOptions);  
 var consumer3 = new ActionBlock<int>(val => {  
 results3.Add(val);  
 Console.WriteLine($"3 consumed: {val}");  
 }, consumerOptions);
